Risk Analysis

What is risk?


  • Uncertainty associated with the returns of an investment

  • Volatility

    • Often measured with Standard Deviation or Variance of returns

Value at Risk (VaR) Assessment



Sharpe Ratio


The Sharpe Ratio is calculated using the formula:


Sharpe Ratio = 𝑅𝑝"𝑅𝑓

#𝑝


where:

  • 𝑅𝑃 is the average return of the portfolio (or stock).

  • 𝑅𝑓 is the risk-free rate.

  • 𝜎𝑝 is the standard deviation of the portfolio’s excess returns.


A higher Sharpe Ratio is better. A negative Sharpe Ratio indicates that the investment's return is less than the risk-free rate.

Sortino Ratio


The Sortino Ratio is calculated using the following formula:


Sortino Ratio = 𝑅𝑝"𝑅𝑓

#𝑑


where:

  • 𝑅𝑃 is the average return of the portfolio (or stock).

  • 𝑅𝑓 is the risk-free rate.

  • 𝜎𝑑 is the downside deviation (standard deviation of negative asset returns).


    A higher Sortino Ratio indicates a more favorable risk-adjusted return when considering only downside risk.

    Model Selection - Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)


    Objective of OLS:


    The goal of OLS is to find the values of 𝛽𝑛 that minimize the sum of the squared residuals (errors) between the observed values of Y and the values predicted by the linear model.

    The squared residuals are calculated as:

    ε𝑖² = (𝑌𝑖 - Ŷ𝑖)²,

    where ε𝑖 is the residual for observation i, 𝑌𝑖 is the observed value, and Ŷ𝑖 is the predicted value.

    Minimization of the Residual Sum of Squares (RSS):


    OLS minimizes the sum of the squared residuals, often referred to as the Residual Sum of Squares (RSS):

    RSS = Σ(ε𝑖²) for all data points.

    The values of 𝛽𝑜 and 𝛽1 that minimize the RSS are the OLS estimates of the model parameters.

    Parameter Estimates:


    The OLS estimates of 𝛽𝑜 and 𝛽1 are given by formulas that provide the best-fitting linear model for the data:

    • 𝛽1 = Σ((𝑋𝑖 - XM)(𝑌𝑖 - Ȳ)) / Σ((𝑋𝑖 - XM)²),

      where 𝑋𝑖 is an observed value of the independent variable, XM is the mean of X, 𝑌𝑖 is an observed value of the dependent variable, and Ȳ is the mean of Y.

    • 𝛽𝑜 = Ȳ - 𝛽1 *XM.

Model Selection- ARIMA



Auto Regressive (AR) Component (p):


The AR component represents the relationship between the current value in the time series and its past values, also known as lags.

The parameter 'p' indicates the order of the AR component, which represents how many past values are used for prediction.

  • For example, if 'p' is 2, the current value is modeled as a linear combination of the two previous values.

Integrated (I) Component (d):


The ‘I’ component represents the differencing of the time series data to make it stationary.

Stationarity is important because many time series

forecasting methods, including ARIMA, assume that the data is stationary, meaning its statistical properties do not change over time.

The parameter 'd' indicates the order of differencing applied to the data. If 'd' is 1, it means that the first differences (the difference between consecutive values) are taken to remove trends.

Moving Average (MA) Component (q):


The MA component models the relationship between the current value and past forecast errors (residuals).

The parameter 'q' indicates the order of the MA component, which represents how many past forecast errors are used for prediction.

ARIMA Development

ARIMA(2,1,0):

  1. ARIMA: Stands for AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average, which is a type of time series model.

  2. (2,1,0): Specifies the non-seasonal part of the

model.

2: Represents the order of the AutoRegressive (AR) component. In this case, it's 2, indicating that the model includes two lagged values of the time series in the prediction.

1: Represents the order of differencing (I). A value of 1 indicates that the time series was differenced once to make it stationary (i.e., to remove trends).

0: Represents the order of the Moving Average

(MA) component. In this case, it's 0, indicating that the model does not include the MA component in the non-seasonal part.

ARIMA Development

(2,1,0)[12]:

(2,1,0): Specifies the seasonal part of the model.

2: Represents the seasonal order of the AutoRegressive (SAR) component. It means that the model includes two lagged seasonal values in the prediction.

1: Represents the seasonal order of

differencing (seasonal I). A value of 1 indicates that seasonal differencing was applied once to the time series.

0: Represents the seasonal order of the Moving Average (SMA) component. In this case, it's 0, indicating that the model does not include the seasonal MA component.

[12]: Indicates that the seasonal pattern has a

period of 12. This means that the model considers a seasonal cycle that repeats every 12 data points (e.g., every 2 weeks).

Conclusions


OLS Wins

- ARIMA is univariate, and can only be trained on one column of data


The RMSE achieved in both models for gold is much larger compared to silver. Why is this?

Throughout our analysis, we noticed that gold and silver showed little correlation to common economic metrics such as inflation and GDP. They shared a lot of correlation to each other, however, which is why their predictions are so similar.


Asset trends like gold and silver are affected by complicated, geopolitical events that are very difficult to reflect in a model. Thus, it’s difficult to get an excellent model.
